ring.message:
Revert "Fix bug #12993929 Screen orientation change replaces wifi password dialog with Add network dialog"

This reverts commit 6b2208dce9a6c561848471608e1ab6188bba80db.

Change-Id: I4936c6f00925abe5db345947ed770f1d50d11a70
message:
Fix bug #12993929 Screen orientation change replaces wifi password dialog with Add network dialog

- do not make inactive the fragment when its transition animation is ending.
Long explanation:

Context: you need to have a first fragment pushed and then a second one replacing
the first one, and then create a DialogFragment on top of it. The FragmentManager
has then three "active" Fragments.

The mActive ArrayList of the FragmentManager is then containing:

mActive[0] = first fragment
mActive[1] = second fragment (parent of the dialog fragment)
mActive[2[ = dialog fragment

Then suppose you are changing the orientation.

During the restoration of the FragmentManager states, you will see that the
first Fragment is marked "inactive" and the mActive ArrayList is looking like:

mActive[0] = dialog fragment
mActive[1] = second fragment

which leads first to have a call to onCreateDialog() for the DialogFragment and
before it can be able to restore its state thru the calls to onCreate() and
onCreateView() for the parent (the second fragment).

Change-Id: I75c9add062ec425417924e6667dd534a1ddfa530

message:
Disable adding main and non moving spaces to immune region in GSS

Disabled adding the main and non moving space to the immune region.
This will enable us to recycle bump pointer spaces for malloc space
-> malloc space compaction as well as collector transitions.

Also added logic for falling back to the non moving space, we may
copy objects there.

Refactored mod union table logic into MarkReachableObjects.

No measurable performance benefit or regression.

Change-Id: Ie43d0ff4f8ec4edba5b4fb5ccacd941f81ac6557
Signed-off-by: Bernhard Rosenkraenzer <Bernhard.Rosenkranzer@linaro.org>
review:
Christopher Ferris: Code-Review+2 Verified+1

I just added a quick test of wmemmove.
Christopher Ferris: Reverted

This patchset was reverted in change: Id89fe959ea5105cd58dff6bba8d91a30cc4bcb07
ring.review:
Bernhard Rosenkränzer: FWIW fd0ce866ce46ed62aa17dc2959a085cb3bf5755d has already been reverted and there's a proper bcopy implementation now, but it probably still makes sense to #define it away for the sake of brevity and saving the argument swapping.
Bernhard Rosenkränzer: Another thing that could potentially go wrong with having just the #defines is C++ constructs like

namespace something {
   using ::bcopy;
}

or any attempt to dlopen libc.so and get a bcopy symbol that way.

I don't think either of those exist in the real world though (C++ users will likely use memmove/memcpy anyway, if only because they're part of the C++ standard -- and dlopening libc for standard functions seems an extremely obscure thing to do).
Bernhard Rosenkränzer: #define-ing bcopy and bzero would make most sense because it would avoid the need for argument switching -- but in reality, there will be binaries seeking to call into libc's bcopy and bzero symbols (probably including half the binary-only drivers already out there).

IMO it makes sense to do both though - add an implementation with argument switching (working on it) to please anything looking for the symbol, but #define bcopy and bzero away in standard headers so newly compiled code gets the slightly faster versions that don't need to move stuff around.
Elliott Hughes: should we just #define bzero and friends to the standard functions in LP64?
Elliott Hughes: > #define-ing bcopy and bzero would make most sense because it would
 > avoid the need for argument switching -- but in reality, there will
 > be binaries seeking to call into libc's bcopy and bzero symbols
 > (probably including half the binary-only drivers already out
 > there).

that's why i said LP64 --- no need to worry about legacy binaries there, though that's exactly why we need to do this _now_ if we're going to do it :-)
Bernhard Rosenkränzer: Found the problem - if it detects there's no overlap, bcopy jumps to memcpy, and assumes the arguments are in the right order (when they're actually reversed).
Working on a fix.
Bernhard Rosenkränzer: We already have that check.
The 1 cpu cycle bzero can save is that check.

From the memset implementation:

#ifdef BZERO
        b       .Lzero_mem
#endif
        ands    A_lw, val, #255
        b.eq    .Lzero_mem

--> bzero is faster by one less ``ands`` instruction.

Probably the same/similar for the other architectures.

Probably not worth keeping just for the sake of this, I doubt there's any code where 1 instruction in memset startup code matters.
Bernhard Rosenkränzer: bzero can actually be a couple of cycles faster than memset 0 (e.g. in arch-arm64/generic/bionic/memset.S saves a call to ands A_lw, val, #255 because the value is guaranteed to be 0), so if we want to save every possible CPU power, bzero can stay (OTOH its presence makes code bigger).

bcopy is entirely useless though, it's never faster than memmove and should be #define-d away for performance.

I'm fairly certain glibc puts it in as a symbol only because standards say it's a function.
Christopher Ferris: Reverted

This patchset was reverted in change: Idc2aa838cf7b65790a1fd26e647f8beb96fdae3a
Elliott Hughes: > bzero can actually be a couple of cycles faster than memset 0 (e.g.
 > in arch-arm64/generic/bionic/memset.S saves a call to ands A_lw,
 > val, #255 because the value is guaranteed to be 0), so if we want
 > to save every possible CPU power, bzero can stay (OTOH its presence
 > makes code bigger).

is we care about that, we'd probably be better off adding a check for 0 in memset and having a memset fastpath for the common case.

 > bcopy is entirely useless though, it's never faster than memmove
 > and should be #define-d away for performance.
 > 
 > I'm fairly certain glibc puts it in as a symbol only because
 > standards say it's a function.

standards say it was removed in POSIX 2008:

http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/xrat/V4_xsh_chap03.html
Christopher Ferris: I forgot to mention that I looked at glibc and they do not use a macro to define the bcopy.
Elliott Hughes: > I forgot to mention that I looked at glibc and they do not use a
 > macro to define the bcopy.

yeah, the fact that glibc doesn't do it is the only reason i hadn't done it already :-)

since these aren't ``std`` functions, we know people won't be using the namespace std { using ... } trick, and i think anyone trying to put bzero and friends into a namespace can reasonably be said to be on their own anyway :-)

ring.message:
Revert "gralloc: Add asynchronous lock/unlock API"

This reverts commit 2861789f4febe67e39de449488681edf3e98b6e2.

Change-Id: I334b8ca9b9fdef510df514c18aabb6a593dfaa75
message:
gralloc: Add asynchronous lock/unlock API

The existing API exposed to clients for software lock/unlock forces the gralloc
implementation to complete these operations synchronously. This change adds new
entry points for lock/unlock functionality that is suited for use with Android's
explicit synchronisation concept. This provides scope for the gralloc module
to internally optimise the work it must do for lock/unlock and to hide this cost
from the client.

Change-Id: I6c41f4a532b705fc76c7777b2f04ea293506b381
review:
Greg Hackmann: Reverted.  Regrettably this caused build breakages due to it triggering a C++ feature (non-trivial designated initializers) which gcc doesn't currently support.  I'll resubmit once I have a non-build-breaking alternative, or audit all our internal gralloc implementations to work around the breakage.
Greg Hackmann: Reverted

This patchset was reverted in change: I334b8ca9b9fdef510df514c18aabb6a593dfaa75

Change-Id: I3e24b50c1d2bf647ed941fefbfa0a0a04375571d
message:
mm-video-v4l2: vdec: Retain lock while querying C2D filled length

On port reconfig, c2d is torn down & reopened. This can trigger a
race condition with any c2d call in the component context. Hold
the c2d lock while querying filled length to avoid this race
condition

Bug: 17692582
